    bio: 'Simone de Beauvoir was born on January 9, 1908, in Paris, into a bourgeois Catholic family whose financial decline during her childhood profoundly shaped her intellectual independence. A brilliant student, she studied philosophy at the Sorbonne, where she met Jean-Paul Sartre in 1929 — they became lifelong intellectual and romantic partners, though their relationship defied every convention of the era. She passed the agrégation in philosophy at the age of 21, becoming the youngest person ever to do so at that time, and went on to teach in lycées across France before devoting herself fully to writing.\n\nBeauvoir\'s philosophical masterwork, The Second Sex (1949), is widely regarded as one of the foundational texts of modern feminism. In it, she applied existentialist philosophy to the condition of women, arguing that "one is not born, but rather becomes, a woman" — that femininity is not a biological essence but a social construction imposed by patriarchal culture. The book was revolutionary in its scope, drawing on history, biology, psychoanalysis, literature, and phenomenology to demonstrate how women had been systematically relegated to the status of the "Other." It was both celebrated and condemned upon publication, placed on the Vatican\'s Index of Forbidden Books, and went on to influence generations of feminist thinkers and activists worldwide.\n\nBeyond The Second Sex, Beauvoir made significant contributions to existentialist ethics in works such as The Ethics of Ambiguity (1947), where she argued that human freedom is always situated and interdependent — that genuine freedom requires not just individual liberation but solidarity with others in their struggle for emancipation. She was also a distinguished novelist, winning the Prix Goncourt for The Mandarins (1954), and a memoirist whose multivolume autobiography remains an unparalleled account of intellectual life in twentieth-century France. She died on April 14, 1986, in Paris, and was buried alongside Sartre in the Cimetière du Montparnasse.',
